== Problem Overview

State the problem clearly. Focus on what is missing, broken, unknown, or inefficient in the current state of the field. The discussion should move from broad context to a precise statement of the unresolved issue. If the proposal includes a system, platform, or framework, this section is also a good place to introduce it at a high level before the technical details appear later.

=== Illustrative Subproblem

This paragraph is the first one after the heading, so it starts flush left. It demonstrates the opening paragraph style used in the template when a new section or subsection begins.

This second paragraph demonstrates the indented continuation style. Use this pattern when you want separation between paragraphs to come from the first-line indent rather than from extra vertical space.

==== Scope Note

Use a fourth-level heading sparingly. In a thesis or proposal, it is most useful when a short, tightly bounded clarification needs its own label without becoming a full new section.

== Document Structure

Briefly orient the reader to the remaining chapters. For example, explain where the literature review, research questions, methodology, and timeline are described. The template includes cross-references so that you can see how a longer academic document hangs together; for instance, the methodology chapter later demonstrates a numbered equation and a summary table.
